This notebook implements the same task—learning the AND logic gate—using two different frameworks. The PyTorch version first builds a small dataset of the four AND-gate input/output pairs as tensors, then defines a FeedforwardNN class with one hidden layer (2→4 neurons via fc1, followed by a ReLU activation) and an output layer (4→1 via fc2, followed by Sigmoid to squash the result into a 0–1 probability)
it then creates an instance of this model along with BCELoss (binary cross-entropy, suited for binary classification) and the Adam optimizer, and runs a training loop for 100 epochs where each iteration computes predictions, calculates the loss against true labels, resets gradients (zero_grad), backpropagates the loss (loss.backward), and updates weights (optimizer.step)
  finally, it switches off gradient tracking (torch.no_grad) to run inference on the same inputs and prints each prediction alongside the rounded probability and the thresholded binary class (1 if ≥0.5, else 0). The Keras/TensorFlow version does the same conceptual job with less boilerplate: it builds the identical AND-gate dataset as NumPy arrays, then uses Sequential to stack layers declaratively
    two ReLU-activated hidden layers (8 and 4 units) and a Sigmoid output layer—compiles the model in one call by specifying the Adam optimizer, binary cross-entropy loss, and accuracy as a tracked metric, trains it with a single model.fit() call that internally handles the forward pass, loss computation, backpropagation, and weight updates for 100 epochs, and then calls model.predict() to get probabilities for each input, which are again thresholded at 0.5 to produce final class labels. Both examples illustrate the same feedforward architecture concep
      input layer → hidden layer(s) with non-linear activation → output layer with sigmoid for binary classification—just expressed through PyTorch's explicit, manual training loop style versus Keras's higher-level, compile-and-fit abstraction.
